	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Seminar on EPA implementation held</h1>

			
			<h4>
												07 June 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>With the first meeting of the Caribbean-EU EPA Council having taken place on the fringes of the EU-Latin American and Caribbean summit in Madrid, attention is turning to the implementation of the Caribbean-EU EPA. At a seminar in Barbados in May 2010, the head of the EPA implementation unit in Barbados argued that ‘while the EPA is not a “miracle cure” for the region, it is expected to facilitate economic restructuring and growth by helping the CARIFORUM countries to move towards more value-added economic activity and to develop a greater capacity to compete internationally in service exports.’ A representative of the Trinidad &amp; Tobago Manufacturers’ Association (TTMA), Mahindra Ramesh Ramdeen, for his part argued that the agreement ‘enhanced the supply chain linkages with the EU’ and provided ‘an opportunity for manufacturers to utilise high-quality and cheaper sources of raw materials to be incorporated into their production process. This has the potential to reduce the cost of manufacturing and increase the quality of products manufactured in a developing region.’</p><p>Eurostat figures circulated before the EU-Latin America &amp; Caribbean summit show that while overall Caribbean exports to the EU have risen some 16.6%, this is largely attributable to the export performance of Trinidad &amp; Tobago. Some 11 out of 15 CARIFORUM countries have seen the value of their exports to the EU decline. In countries such as St Kitts &amp; Nevis and Grenada, the decline has been a massive 91.7% and 80% respectively, while the value of Jamaican exports to the EU has fallen 60% in euro terms since 2000.</p><p><b>Caribbean exports to the EU27 - 2000 and 2009 (million euro)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="427">
