				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
IPS, press article, ‘Jury still out on trade pact with Europe’, 13 May <br />
<a href="http://ipsnews.net/newsTVE.asp?idnews=51425" target="_self">http://ipsnews.net:80/newsTVE.asp?idnews=51425</a></p><p>
Eurostat, press release, ‘EU27 trade deficit of €9bn with the LAC countries in 2009’, STAT/10/70, 17 May 2010<br />
<a href="http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/cache/ITY_PUBLIC/6-17052010-AP/EN/6-17052010-AP-EN.PDF" target="_self">http://epp.eurostat.ec.europa.eu/cache/ITY_PUBLIC/6-17052010-AP/EN/6-170...</a> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It is apparent from the recent regional seminar in Barbados that most of the opportunities under the EPA lie in the manufacturing and service sector, with little scope outside the Dominican Republic being seen for an expansion of food and agricultural exports. Indeed, with the pace of preference erosion in the banana, sugar and rice sectors accelerating, Caribbean agricultural exports to the EU are likely to continue to decline despite the EPA – the notable exception being the Dominican Republic, where new market opportunities have been opened up through the EPA in formerly quota-restricted areas.</p><p>Eurostat figures suggest a significant decline in the overall EU trade relationship with the Caribbean, a development in sharp contrast to the expanding trade relationship between the EU and Latin American countries over the same period. This decline in exports from many of the CARIFORUM members is attributable to developments in the agricultural sector, notably the process of price reductions in the sugar and rice sectors and the erosion of the market position of Caribbean suppliers in the banana sector.</p>
		</div>
		
